In this article, Jim Carroll, the Deputy Director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy, discusses the opioid epidemic in the United States. He highlights the alarming statistics of drug overdose deaths, which outnumbered deaths caused by motor-vehicle crashes and suicide in 2017. Carroll emphasizes the importance of preventing others from falling into addiction and urges parents and young people to be aware of the risks associated with opioids. He mentions President Trump's dedication to addressing the crisis and the administration's efforts to provide funding and resources to states and local communities. Carroll also encourages individuals to seek help for addiction and provides information on how to safely dispose of prescription opioids and respond to an overdose. He concludes by emphasizing the need for a collaborative approach involving first responders, healthcare professionals, law enforcement officers, educators, and community members to address drug abuse and save lives.